<figureCitation box="[344,411,1574,1601]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="9.[140,174,1622,1644]" captionTargetBox="[140,1109,821,1603]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[141,1109,822,1602]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Fig. 1. Distribution of Colon asperatum, Colon bidentatum, Colon horni, Colon arcum, Colon forceps,Colon schwarzi and Colon incisum in Atlantic Canada." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3773780" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3773780/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="360">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). It was collected in mixed forests between June and August. In general, very little is known about the bionomics of species in the genus 
<emphasis box="[974,1039,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="360">Colon</emphasis>
. They are believed to be associated with subterranean fungi (
<bibRefCitation author="Peck and Stephan" box="[747,1020,1645,1672]" firstAuthor="Peck" pageId="3" pageNumber="360" pagination="667 - 741" refId="ref23890" refString="Peck SB, Stephan K (1996) A revision of the genus Colon Herbst (Coleoptera: Leiodidae: Coloninae) of North America. The Canadian Entomologist 128: 667 - 741." type="journal article" year="1996">Peck and Stephan 1996</bibRefCitation>
